pullRequest.body:
In a locally convex space, the absolutely convex hull of a totally bounded set is totally bounded. The proof given here follows Proposition 3 of Bourbaki TVS II.25.

My current version of Bourbaki's proof is rather long and ugly in the translation between the uniformity and  neighbourhoods of a point . Whilst there is scope for golfing the current proof, I wonder if I am barking up the wrong tree and there is some other way I should be doing this?

---

The better way to state this would be to assume `[UniformSpace E] [UniformAddGroup E]`. It feels a bit weird from the math point of view since the uniformity comes from the topology, but in many case it won't be defeq to `TopologicalAddGroup.toUniformSpace` (e.g your current lemma does not apply to normed spaces !). And it avoids a bunch of troubles in the proof.

Another thing : I think I would rather first state the result about the convex hull, and then use `convexHull_union_neg_eq_absConvexHull` to deduce the current result. I know Bourbaki does it the other way around (after all, what you wrote is stronger), but since we will have to *state* the convex hull statement anyway (which they don't !) I think we might as well split up the proof.
But of course this is a matter of taste

Have you tried using [totallyBounded_iff_subset_finite_iUnion_nhds_zero](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Algebra/UniformGroup.html#totallyBounded_iff_subset_finite_iUnion_nhds_zero) ? I think it will make your life way easier.
I think you'd make your life easier by just using `V + V` directly. Of course both are equal, but introducing smul here can only cause harm I think.
Thanks - that's much better - in fact gives us a more general result for `V+W`.
